<p>Indiana's humid continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment capable of handling both extreme heat and cold. Summer temperatures regularly reach the upper 80s and low 90s Fahrenheit, with humidity levels that make conditions feel significantly hotter. These conditions place substantial demands on air conditioning systems, making efficiency crucial for controlling energy costs. The state's summers typically require cooling systems to operate continuously during peak periods, emphasizing the importance of proper sizing and high SEER ratings.</p>

