<h2>Indiana Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Indiana offers several attractive incentives for solar panel and HVAC installations that significantly reduce project costs. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation, and permits. Indiana residents can combine this federal credit with state and local incentives for maximum savings.</p>

<p>The state of Indiana provides a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added value from solar panels does not increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the system. Additionally, Indiana does not charge sales tax on solar equipment, providing immediate savings during purchase. These tax benefits make solar installations more affordable and improve long-term returns on investment.</p>

<p>Duke Energy Indiana offers several rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment and solar installations. The utility's Home Energy House Call program provides rebates up to \$1,000 for qualifying heat pumps, furnaces, and air conditioning systems. Solar customers can participate in Duke Energy's net metering program, receiving credit for excess electricity fed back to the grid. The utility also offers time-of-use rates that can benefit solar customers who generate power during peak demand periods.</p>

<p>Many Indiana municipalities and counties offer additional incentives for renewable energy and energy efficiency improvements. The Indiana Office of Energy Development maintains updated information on available programs, which can include low-interest loans, additional tax credits, and grant programs for qualifying installations. Some local utilities beyond Duke Energy offer their own rebate programs, making it important for homeowners to research all available incentives in their specific service territory.</p>

<h2>Combining Solar and HVAC Systems</h2>

<p>The integration of solar panels with high-efficiency HVAC systems creates exceptional value for Indiana homeowners. Solar energy production peaks during summer months when air conditioning demand is highest, allowing solar panels to directly offset cooling costs. This natural alignment between solar generation and cooling demand maximizes the financial benefits of both systems. Modern heat pumps can also be powered by solar energy during milder weather, further reducing reliance on grid electricity.</p>

<p>Smart home technology enables optimal coordination between solar production and HVAC operation. Programmable thermostats can be configured to pre-cool homes during peak solar production hours, storing cooling in the building's thermal mass for later use. This strategy reduces grid electricity consumption during expensive peak rate periods while maximizing the use of free solar energy. Advanced systems can even predict weather patterns and adjust HVAC operation accordingly.</p>

<p>Battery storage systems are becoming increasingly popular additions to solar and HVAC combinations in Indiana. Tesla Powerwalls, Enphase batteries, and other storage solutions allow homeowners to store excess solar energy for use during evening hours when HVAC systems continue operating but solar panels are not producing. This capability provides energy independence and protection against power outages while maximizing the value of solar generation.</p>

